insert into public.questions
  (id, parent_id, type, category, subtopic, importance, difficulty, candidate_level, region, question, key_points, model_answer)
values
(1980, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$LBO Floor Value$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$In a sale process you keep hearing that the LBO analysis sets the valuation floor. Walk me through why a sponsor's maximum affordable price acts as a floor, and what would push that floor up or down in today's market.$x$, $x$["LBO Solves For Entry Price At Target IRR", "Floor = Highest Price A Sponsor Can Pay And Still Hit Return Hurdle", "Strategics Usually Pay More Due To Synergies And Lower Cost Of Capital", "Inputs: Leverage Available Exit Multiple Cash Flow Hold Period", "Higher-For-Longer Rates And Tighter Private Credit Lower The Floor", "Floor Not Ceiling Sets Walk-Away In Auction"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The LBO floor is just the flip side of how a sponsor solves the model. Instead of asking what is this worth, the sponsor fixes a target return, say a low-to-mid twenties IRR or a 2 to 2.5x multiple of money, then solves backward for the most they can pay at entry and still clear that hurdle. That maximum affordable price is the floor because a financial sponsor will only ever bid up to it, while strategic buyers can usually pay more since they layer in synergies and have a lower cost of capital. So in an auction the LBO price tends to set the lower bound of the range, and strategics or a competitive process push you above it. What moves the floor is leverage available, the cost and amount of debt, the assumed exit multiple, the free cash flow for paydown, and the hold period. In a higher-for-longer rate world with tighter private credit and pricier debt, the same return hurdle implies a lower entry price, so the floor drops. I would frame it to the board as the sponsor walk-away, not the ceiling.$x$),
(1981, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Accretion Dilution Lens$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Beyond a DCF or comps, how can accretion and dilution analysis be used as a value lens to judge what an acquirer can afford to pay? Walk me through the intuition and the breakeven price.$x$, $x$["Compares Acquirer Earnings Yield To Deal Cost Of Funding", "Cheaper-PE Target Funded With Richer Stock Is Accretive", "Breakeven Price Where Combined Pro Forma EPS Unchanged", "Cash And Debt Funding Versus Stock Mix Drives Result", "Affordability Check Not Intrinsic Value", "Synergies Raise The Breakeven Affordable Price", "Watch EPS Accretion Masking Value Destruction"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Accretion dilution flips the question from what is it worth to what can I pay before my own EPS goes down. The intuition is a yield comparison. If I fund the deal with stock, I am effectively swapping my acquirer earnings yield, the inverse of my P/E, against the target's. A target bought at a lower P/E than my own stock is accretive, and one bought richer is dilutive. With cash or debt funding, the comparison is the target's after-tax earnings yield versus the after-tax cost of the debt or the foregone interest on cash. The value lens is the breakeven price, the price at which combined pro forma EPS is unchanged. Solve for that and you have a ceiling driven purely by financing math rather than intrinsic value. Then synergies extend how much you can pay and still stay accretive, so I would show the breakeven with and without them. The big caveat is that accretion is not value creation. A deal can be EPS accretive and still destroy value if you overpay or take on a structurally worse business, so I use it as an affordability and market-optics check alongside DCF, never as the valuation itself.$x$),
(1982, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Venture Capital Method$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A pre-revenue startup is raising a seed round and asks you to value it. Walk me through the venture-capital method and how you get from an exit value back to a pre-money valuation today.$x$, $x$["Estimate Exit Value Via Exit Multiple Or Comp Acquisition", "Discount Back At High Target VC IRR Over The Holding Period", "Post-Money = Exit Value Divided By The Compounded Required Return", "Subtract New Investment To Get Pre-Money", "Adjust For Future Dilution From Later Rounds", "High Discount Rate Reflects Failure Risk And Illiquidity", "Sanity-Check Implied Ownership For The Stage"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The venture-capital method works backward from an exit rather than forward from cash flows, because a pre-revenue company has no meaningful cash flows to discount. I start by estimating the exit value, usually by taking projected revenue or earnings a few years out at a plausible exit and applying an exit multiple from comparable acquisitions or IPOs in that space. Then I discount that exit value back to today, but at a very high target return, often something like a 40 to 60 percent IRR or a target multiple of money, which reflects the high failure rate, illiquidity, and the fact that most of a portfolio relies on a few winners. Exit value divided by that compounded required return gives the post-money valuation today, and I subtract the new money going in to get the pre-money. The crucial refinement is dilution. Since later rounds will issue more shares, I have to adjust for expected future dilution, otherwise the investor's final ownership is overstated. I would also flip it around and check the implied ownership the investor takes for their check against what is normal for the stage, as a reality test on the number.$x$),
(1983, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Scorecard Method$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$An angel investor asks how to value a pre-revenue company without any financials to model. Explain the scorecard method and when it is more useful than a discounted-cash-flow or venture-capital approach.$x$, $x$["Start From Average Pre-Money For Region And Stage", "Adjust Up Or Down On Qualitative Factors", "Factors: Team Market Size Product Competition Traction", "Weight Each Factor And Apply Multiplier To Benchmark", "Relative Method Anchored To Local Market Comps", "Better When No Projections Are Credible", "Subjective So Use As A Cross-Check"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The scorecard method, sometimes called the Bill Payne method, values an early company by benchmarking it against the typical funded startup in the same region and stage rather than by modeling cash flows. You start with the average pre-money valuation for comparable seed deals in that market, then adjust that baseline up or down across a set of weighted qualitative factors. The usual factors are the management team, which carries the most weight, the size of the opportunity, the product and technology, the competitive environment, the sales channels, and any early traction. You score the company against the norm on each factor, apply the weights, and the blended multiplier scales the benchmark. So an exceptional team and a huge market in an otherwise average field might land at, say, 1.2 times the regional average. It is genuinely more useful than a DCF or even the VC method when there are no credible projections at all, because it leans on real comparables instead of fabricated forecasts. The weakness is that it is subjective and only as good as your comp set, so I treat it as one cross-check rather than the answer.$x$),
(1984, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Equity As Call Option$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A highly leveraged company is trading near insolvency, yet its equity still has value. Using the idea that equity is a call option on the firm's assets, explain why, and how Black-Scholes intuition values that equity.$x$, $x$["Equity = Call Option On Assets Struck At Debt Face Value", "Limited Liability Gives Optionality Payoff At Maturity", "Inputs: Asset Value Strike Debt Time Volatility Rate", "Higher Asset Volatility Raises Equity Value Even When Distressed", "Out-Of-The-Money But Time Value Keeps Equity Positive", "Shareholder Versus Creditor Wealth-Transfer Incentive", "Use When Assets Near Or Below Debt"]$x$::jsonb, $x$With limited liability, shareholders own a call option on the firm's assets with a strike equal to the face value of the debt. At maturity, if assets exceed what is owed, equity holders pay off the debt and keep the residual, the in-the-money payoff. If assets fall short, they walk away and hand the keys to creditors, so their downside is floored at zero. That payoff is exactly a call. So even when a firm is deeply distressed and assets sit below the debt, the equity is not worthless, it is an out-of-the-money option with time value. In Black-Scholes terms, the underlying is the market value of the firm's assets, the strike is the debt's face value, the maturity is roughly the debt's tenor, plus asset volatility and the risk-free rate. The striking implication is that higher asset volatility raises equity value, because more dispersion makes the upside tail more valuable while the downside stays capped at zero. That is why distressed shareholders favor risky bets, a wealth transfer from creditors. I would use this contingent-claim lens precisely when a DCF or multiples break down and assets are near or below the debt load.$x$),
(1985, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$No Clean Comps$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$You are asked to value a one-of-a-kind business with no clean public comparables - a novel category leader with no listed peer. How do you build a defensible valuation without a direct comp set?$x$, $x$["Lead With Intrinsic DCF As Primary Anchor", "Build Synthetic Peer Set From Business-Model Analogs", "Decompose Into Comparable Segments Or Value Drivers", "Use Operating-Metric Multiples Not Just Earnings", "Triangulate Private Rounds And M And A Datapoints", "Cross-Check With Sum-Of-The-Parts", "Flag Wide Range And Stress Key Assumptions"]$x$::jsonb, $x$When there is no clean public peer, I stop hunting for a perfect comp and triangulate from several imperfect angles. The primary anchor becomes an intrinsic DCF, because it stands on the company's own cash flows rather than borrowed multiples, so I spend my effort on a defensible forecast, discount rate, and terminal value. Then I build a synthetic comp set out of business-model analogs rather than industry twins. If the company is unique in its sector but shares economics with subscription software, a marketplace, or a logistics network, I borrow those multiples and adjust for growth and margin. I also decompose the business: if different parts resemble different known models, I value each on its own logic and sum the parts. Because earnings may be thin, I lean on operating-metric multiples like value per user, per transaction, or per unit of capacity. I triangulate with whatever private rounds or M and A datapoints exist, since those are real prices for similar assets. Finally I present it honestly as a wide range with the key swing assumptions stress-tested, rather than pretending one number is precise.$x$),
(1986, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Liquidation And Replacement$x$, 'standard', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$A struggling asset-heavy company may be worth more dead than alive. Walk me through liquidation value and asset-based or replacement-cost valuation, and when each sets the relevant value rather than a going-concern method.$x$, $x$["Going-Concern Versus Liquidation Value Comparison", "Orderly Versus Forced Liquidation Haircuts By Asset Class", "Liquidation = Asset Recovery Less Liabilities And Wind-Down Costs", "Replacement Cost = Greenfield Cost To Rebuild Assets", "Floor Value When Earnings Power Is Negative", "Waterfall And Priority Of Claims In Distress", "Relevant For Holdcos Real Estate Heavy Industrials"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The starting question is whether the business is worth more as a going concern or broken up, and you take the higher. Liquidation value asks what you net selling the assets piecemeal and paying off liabilities. I haircut each asset class by recovery rate, cash near full, receivables and inventory less, specialized fixed assets often a steep discount, then subtract liabilities plus wind-down costs like severance. Orderly liquidation over time recovers more than a forced fire sale. In a US bankruptcy you respect the claims waterfall, secured first, then unsecured, then equity, so liquidation often shows equity is wiped out. Replacement cost comes from the other side, what it would cost to rebuild the asset base from scratch, the greenfield cost, useful for capital-intensive plant, real estate, or infrastructure, and it caps what a rational buyer pays versus building their own. Either asset-based method becomes the relevant value rather than a DCF when earnings power is negative or the assets are worth more than the cash flows they throw off, so they act as a floor, common for distressed holdcos and heavy industrials.$x$),
(1987, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Pre-Revenue Operating Metrics$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A fast-growing consumer app is pre-revenue but has explosive user growth. With no sales to multiply, how do you value it on operating metrics, and how do you avoid the classic traps with KPI-based valuation?$x$, $x$["Value On Engaged Users GMV Or Bookings Not Revenue", "Derive Value-Per-User From M And A Or Funding Comps", "Build A Forward Path To Monetization And Unit Economics", "Test With Cohort Retention And LTV-To-CAC", "Risk Of Vanity Metrics And Pull-Forward Growth", "Triangulate Against Forward Revenue Multiple Once Monetized", "Wide Range Scenario-Weight Outcomes"]$x$::jsonb, $x$With no revenue to multiply, I value the asset on the operating metric that best proxies future monetization, then pressure-test that the metric will convert to cash. For a consumer app that usually means engaged or monthly active users, gross merchandise value, or bookings rather than headline downloads. I derive an implied value per engaged user from recent M and A or funding rounds for similar apps, apply it, and treat that as one read. The discipline is to layer a path to monetization on top, what revenue per user is realistic, at what take rate or ad load, with what margin, so the metric ties back to economics. I check user quality with cohort retention and lifetime value against acquisition cost, since growth funded by unsustainable spend is worth little. The classic traps are vanity metrics, registered instead of active users, and pull-forward growth from promotions that does not retain. Once even a sliver of revenue exists, I triangulate against a forward revenue multiple, and I present it as a wide, scenario-weighted range, since the gap between monetization working and failing is enormous.$x$),
(1988, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Price Versus Value$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$In a live negotiation a client says your intrinsic valuation says one number but the other side is anchored somewhere else entirely. Explain the difference between price and intrinsic value, and how you use intrinsic value when the negotiated price won't match it.$x$, $x$["Intrinsic Value From Fundamentals Price From Negotiation", "Price Set By Supply Demand Leverage And Alternatives", "Synergies And Strategic Value Drive A Wedge", "Intrinsic Value Sets Walk-Away And Reservation Price", "Football Field Frames Range Not A Point", "BATNA And Process Dynamics Move Final Price", "Avoid Winners Curse Discipline Around Floor"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Price and value are related but not the same, and a negotiation is where that gap becomes real. Intrinsic value is what the business is worth on fundamentals, the present value of its cash flows, what my DCF says it should be. Price is whatever two parties actually agree to, driven by negotiation, supply and demand, each side's leverage, and their alternatives, not by a model. A strategic buyer with synergies or a scarcity of assets can rationally pay above standalone intrinsic value, while a forced seller may take less. So when the negotiated price will not match my number, intrinsic value does not become useless, it changes job. It becomes the discipline, the anchor for the client's reservation price and walk-away. I would frame value as a range, a football field, rather than a single point, and use it to say here is the floor below which we do not sell, or the ceiling above which the buyer overpays and triggers the winner's curse. The final price is then a function of process dynamics and each side's best alternative, the BATNA, but intrinsic value is what keeps the client from negotiating into a bad deal.$x$),
(1989, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$DCF Scenario And Tornado$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$You have a base-case DCF on an industrial target at about 2 billion enterprise value. The MD wants to see how robust that number is. Walk me through how you would set up scenario analysis, a sensitivity table, and a tornado chart, and what each one actually tells the client.$x$, $x$["Scenario = internally consistent bundles (bull base bear)", "Sensitivity table = two-variable grid, usually WACC vs terminal growth or exit multiple", "Tornado = one variable at a time, ranked by EV impact", "Tornado identifies which drivers matter most", "Hold other inputs at base when flexing one", "Output is a range, not a point estimate", "Communicates key risks to client, not just a number"]$x$::jsonb, $x$So these three tools answer different questions, and I would show all three. Scenario analysis bundles inputs into internally consistent cases - a bull, base and bear - where I flex revenue growth, margins, capex and exit assumptions together, because in the real world they move together. The two-variable sensitivity table is the classic data table - I usually put WACC across the top and terminal growth or exit multiple down the side, and read enterprise value in each cell, holding everything else at base. That isolates the two assumptions the value is most levered to. The tornado chart is the diagnostic - I flex one driver at a time across a plausible high-low range, holding the rest at base, then rank the resulting EV swings widest to narrowest, so the bars form a tornado. It tells the client which assumptions actually move the answer, usually WACC, growth and margin, so we know where to focus diligence. The honest framing is that a DCF gives a range, not a point, and these show how wide and why.$x$),
(1990, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Tornado Versus Scenario$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$In your DCF deck you have both a tornado chart and a three-case scenario summary. The client asks why you need both - don't they show the same thing? How do you defend keeping both, and what is the key methodological difference?$x$, $x$["Tornado = one-at-a-time univariate sensitivity", "Scenario = joint correlated moves across inputs", "Tornado isolates driver importance and ranking", "Scenarios preserve real-world correlation of inputs", "Tornado can mislead by ignoring interactions", "Use tornado to prioritize, then build coherent scenarios", "Both together give importance and plausible range"]$x$::jsonb, $x$They look similar but they answer different questions, so I keep both. The tornado is univariate - I move one input at a time across its plausible range while holding everything else at base, then rank the EV swings. Its whole job is to tell you which single assumptions the valuation is most sensitive to, so you know where to spend diligence. The weakness is that it ignores correlation - in reality, weaker growth usually drags margins and the exit multiple down at the same time, and the tornado never captures that interaction. Scenario analysis fixes exactly that. A bear case moves growth, margins, capex and exit together in an internally consistent story, so it shows a realistic combined outcome rather than a one-variable flex. So the workflow is: use the tornado to find the two or three drivers that matter, then build coherent bull-base-bear scenarios around those drivers. One tells you what to worry about; the other tells you how bad or good it plausibly gets when those things move together. Showing only one leaves a real gap.$x$),
(1991, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Monte Carlo Valuation$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A client running a high-growth business asks whether you can put a probability distribution around your DCF value using a Monte-Carlo simulation instead of just three scenarios. How would you set it up, what does it add over scenarios, and where would you be careful about over-selling the output?$x$, $x$["Assign distributions to key inputs, not point estimates", "Define correlations between drivers", "Run thousands of draws to get an EV distribution", "Output is a probability range, P10 P50 P90", "Adds probabilities scenarios cannot give", "Garbage-in risk: spurious precision from assumed distributions", "Correlation and tail assumptions drive the result"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Conceptually a Monte-Carlo just replaces point estimates with distributions. Instead of a single revenue growth or WACC, I assign each key driver a distribution - say growth as a triangular or normal, margins with a range, maybe the exit multiple - and crucially I specify correlations, because if growth and margin draw independently you get nonsense combinations. Then I run several thousand trials, recompute enterprise value each time, and out comes a full distribution of EV. The advantage over three scenarios is that I can actually talk in probabilities - here is the P10 to P90 range, here is the chance value falls below the offer price - which a bull-base-bear cannot give you. Where I am careful is over-selling the precision. The output looks rigorous, but it is only as good as the input distributions and correlations, which I am largely making up. It can manufacture false confidence and hide that one or two assumptions drive everything. So I present it as a way to frame uncertainty and tail risk, not as a more accurate single number, and I always pair it with the deterministic base case the board can actually anchor on.$x$),
(1992, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Defending Blended Range$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Your football field has five methodologies giving overlapping but different ranges, and the client wants a single blended valuation range to anchor negotiations. How do you decide what weight each method gets, and how do you defend the blended range when the buyer's banker pushes back on it?$x$, $x$["Weight by relevance and reliability, not equal weighting", "Favor methods with cleanest comparables and best data", "Discount outliers and thin or stale datasets", "Blended range should sit where methods overlap", "Tie weights to deal context, buyer type and sector", "Defend with methodology quality, not just averaging", "Show sensitivity and avoid false precision"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I do not just average the five ranges - I weight by how relevant and reliable each method is for this specific asset. The methods with the cleanest, closest comparables and the most reliable inputs get the most weight. For a mature cash-generative business I lean on trading comps and DCF; for a competitive sale process precedent transactions and an LBO floor carry more weight because they reflect what buyers actually pay and what a sponsor can fund. I explicitly down-weight ranges built on thin, stale or non-comparable data, and I treat any methodology that is an obvious outlier with suspicion rather than letting it drag the blend. The blended range should naturally sit where the credible methods overlap - that overlap is the real story, not a mechanical mean. When the buyer's banker pushes back, I do not defend an average; I defend the inputs - why these comps, why this discount rate, why these synergies are excluded from the standalone view. And I show the sensitivities so it is clearly a defensible range anchored in methodology quality, not false precision around a single number.$x$),
(1993, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Banker Versus Research Target$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$You are advising a public company and your valuation range sits well above the consensus equity-research price target on the stock. The CFO asks why the two disagree. How do you reconcile a banker's valuation with a sell-side analyst's price target?$x$, $x$["Price target is standalone where-it-trades, not takeout value", "Banker range includes control premium and synergies", "Different time horizon: 12-month PT versus intrinsic", "Analysts anchor to market sentiment and current multiples", "Methodology differs, often single multiple versus full suite", "Control and strategic value not in a trading target", "Reconcile by bridging the specific drivers of the gap"]$x$::jsonb, $x$They are answering different questions, so a gap is expected. A sell-side price target is a forecast of where the share price trades on a standalone basis over the next twelve months - it is a minority, no-control, market-sentiment view, usually built off a single forward multiple or a light DCF, and it is anchored to how the market is pricing the sector today. My banker range is typically a takeout or intrinsic value: it reflects what a buyer would pay for control, so it includes a control premium and, for a strategic, the value of synergies - none of which belong in a where-it-trades target. There is also a horizon difference; the analyst is looking twelve months out, I am looking at full intrinsic or transaction value. So I reconcile by bridging the gap explicitly - start from the consensus target, add the control premium, layer in synergies if a strategic is in the mix, and adjust for any difference in forward assumptions or multiple. If after that bridge the numbers still do not meet, then either my assumptions or the street's are too aggressive, and that is the conversation to have with the CFO.$x$),
(1994, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Standalone Versus Synergy Value$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$You are advising the seller. The buyer says the business is worth a lot to them because of synergies, so they should not have to pay for that. Walk me through the difference between standalone value and sale value including synergies, and who should capture the synergy value in the price.$x$, $x$["Standalone = value to current owner on its own", "Synergy-inclusive = standalone plus PV of synergies", "Walk-away floor is standalone value for the seller", "Synergies are buyer-specific, created by the deal", "Premium is effectively a share of synergies", "Negotiation splits synergy value between parties", "Seller leverage and competition drive the split"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Standalone value is what the business is worth on its own to its current owners - the intrinsic or trading value with no deal. Sale value including synergies adds the present value of the cost and revenue synergies the buyer can only realize by combining the two businesses. The key point for my seller is that those synergies do not exist without this transaction, and the premium a buyer pays over standalone is, in economic terms, just handing back a slice of that synergy value. So my floor in any negotiation is the standalone value - that is the walk-away. Above that, everything is a split of the synergy pie. The buyer will argue they created the synergies and should keep them; the seller argues that without selling, the buyer captures none, so the seller deserves a meaningful share. Who actually captures it comes down to leverage - how many credible bidders there are, how unique this buyer's synergies are versus the next bidder's, and how badly each side needs the deal. In a competitive auction the seller pushes the price up toward the full synergy-inclusive value; in a bilateral deal the split is more even.$x$),
(1995, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Cash Versus Stock Value$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A buyer can fund an acquisition with cash or with its own stock at the same headline price per share. The seller's board asks if the two offers are really equivalent. Walk me through how cash versus stock consideration changes the value actually delivered to each side and the risks each carries.$x$, $x$["Cash = fixed, certain value to seller at close", "Stock = value floats with acquirer share price", "Stock shares deal risk and synergy upside with the seller", "Exchange ratio fixed versus floating, and collars matter", "Seller tax often deferred in a stock deal", "Acquirer signaling: stock may imply overvalued equity", "Accretion/dilution and balance-sheet capacity for the buyer"]$x$::jsonb, $x$At the same headline price they are not equivalent, because the risk profiles differ. Cash delivers a fixed, certain value to the seller at close - they know exactly what they get and they walk away from deal and integration risk. Stock is a floating value: the seller now holds the acquirer's shares, so what they actually realize moves with the buyer's price through close and beyond, and depends on whether the synergies and combined story play out. So stock keeps the seller exposed to both the downside and upside of the combination - attractive if they believe in the deal, a real risk if they do not. Mechanics matter: is the exchange ratio fixed or floating, and is there a collar protecting against price swings. There is usually a tax angle - a stock deal can let the seller defer tax, whereas cash is typically taxable now. For the buyer, cash uses balance-sheet capacity or debt and tends to be more accretive; issuing stock can signal management thinks its own shares are richly valued, which the market often reads negatively. So I would never tell the board the two offers are the same.$x$),
(1996, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Earnout Bid-Ask Bridge$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Buyer and seller are stuck about a billion apart because they disagree on the target's forward growth. The banker suggests an earnout. Walk me through how a contingent earnout bridges that valuation gap, how you would actually value the contingent piece, and the risks you would warn the client about.$x$, $x$["Earnout bridges a genuine bid-ask gap on future performance", "Buyer pays upfront plus deferred, contingent on hitting targets", "Splits performance risk between buyer and seller", "Value contingent piece as probability-weighted, discounted PV", "Metric choice matters: revenue or milestone cleaner than EBITDA", "Risks: measurement disputes and misaligned incentives", "Tool to close a deal, not a free lunch"]$x$::jsonb, $x$An earnout bridges a genuine disagreement about value - usually the seller's growth forecast looks aggressive to the buyer. Rather than pay the full price upfront, the buyer pays a certain amount at close and defers part of the consideration, contingent on the business hitting agreed targets - revenue, EBITDA, or a milestone like a product launch or approval. So it splits the risk: the seller only collects the contingent piece if their case proves out, and the buyer is protected from overpaying for performance that never shows up. In valuation terms I would not just add the headline earnout to the upfront cash - the contingent payment is a probability-weighted expected value, so I discount it for both the chance of hitting the target and the time value. Structure matters: an EBITDA-based earnout invites disputes over cost allocation and post-close investment, so revenue or a clean milestone is often better. The honest framing is that an earnout narrows a bid-ask gap but creates real friction - measurement disputes, misaligned incentives, accounting volatility - so it is a tool for closing a deal, not a free lunch.$x$),
(1997, NULL, 'primary', $x$Valuation$x$, $x$Strategic Versus Financial Buyer$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$The same asset is in a sale process drawing both strategic acquirers and private-equity sponsors. The seller asks why a strategic can usually pay more for the identical business. Walk me through why a strategic-buyer value differs from a financial-buyer value, and when the sponsor can actually win.$x$, $x$["Strategic captures synergies a financial buyer largely cannot", "Strategic has lower cost of capital and longer horizon", "Financial buyer constrained by required IRR and exit multiple", "Sponsor return driven by leverage and operational improvement", "No synergies, so PE pays closer to standalone", "Sponsor wins on speed, certainty or platform synergies", "Higher-for-longer rates compress sponsor purchasing power"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The core reason is synergies. A strategic already operates in the space, so it can fold the target into its platform, strip out duplicate cost and add revenue - that synergy value lets it justify a higher price and still earn a return, because it is buying standalone value plus a synergy pie a sponsor does not have. The strategic also usually has a lower cost of capital and a longer, sometimes indefinite, holding horizon, so it can underwrite a fuller price. A financial buyer values the same asset on its own cash flows - no operating synergies, so it pays closer to standalone, and it is boxed in by a required IRR and an assumed exit multiple. Its return is driven by leverage, the pace of de-levering and operational improvement, not synergy. So mechanically the strategic ceiling is higher. But sponsors do win - when they offer more speed and certainty, when they run a buy-and-build so a platform company gives them real synergies, or when no strategic is interested. And the catch now is that higher-for-longer rates raise financing costs and compress the leverage a sponsor can support, pushing down what they can pay.$x$) on conflict do nothing;
